text.text: A Guide to Shoreditch

Jekyll and Hyde ain't got shit on shape-shifting Shoreditch. By day, you'll find tranquil lanes brimming with creativity as imaginative, caffeine-fuelled innovators do their creative thing. By night (especially on the weekends) you'll find an unruly, wild beast full of carnal urges and debauchery on every corner.

It's full of places to splurge that disposable dough, with more coffee roasters, clothes shops, smokehouses, intimate cocktail dens and brunch spots than you can shake a stick at. And Shoreditch is the kind of place you could shake your stick without anyone batting an eyelid. We had it Large and lived to tell the tale: this is it.
Best for... a light-filled brunch stop

tip.text:
When the going gets tough in Shoreditch, it's good to know a soothing cafe you can dip into, to get away from all the posers. Visions Canteen offers just that - along with hefty brunch flavours, quality coffee beans and the prerequisite sourdough from Dusty Knuckle Bakery.

Treat your laptop to a studious afternoon in bright, lofty, greenery-filled surrounds; or just take a friend. Their menu is small and changes frequently with a few long standing crowd pleasers and all sorts of exotic twists. If you've an eye for these things, you'll spot all sorts of Korean, Chinese and Thai influences on the menu. We got caught up in the heady flavours of a crab toast with fried eggs, Chinese XO sauce, confit garlic and spring onions; and a minced chicken 'grapow' that boasted bucket loads of zingy Thai spice.

You'll never quite know what to expect with the drinks here either; look out for Mexican-inspired pineapple ferments or whatever other concoctions this lot have dreamt up. All we know is the portions are generous, turmeric lattes creamy and coffee absolutely bang on - so we'll be back for more.

text.text:
When the going gets tough in Shoreditch and you need a place to dip into, hit Visions Canteen. In bright, lofty and greenery-filled surrounds, this place is about hefty brunch flavours, quality coffee beans and doing a little unwinding.

Their menu is small and changes frequently, with a few long standing crowd pleasers and all sorts of exotic twists. We got caught up in the heady flavours of a crab toast with fried eggs, Chinese XO sauce, confit garlic and spring onions; and a minced chicken 'grapow' that boasted bucket loads of zingy Thai spice.
Best for... nostalgic British cooking

tip.text:
Hidden away behind the red brick walls of a converted school - surrounded by a bouncy green lawn, fruit trees and other shrubbery - this restaurant is a pretty magical place: it makes you feel like you're in on a secret. Margot Henderson, the culinary smarts of the operation, cooked in some of the top London restaurants before setting up this little nugget, turning bike sheds into a soothing retreat from the Shoreditch madness. Decor is a thoughtful, modern kind of 'farmhouse chic' with pristine pine furniture and battered straw hats hanging along one wall.

Food - though heavenly - appears similarly effortless: think perfectly seasoned chicken pie, hunks of fuss-free fish and mounds of fresh leaves from the garden. It's the kind of place where lightly stewed plums come with huge sticky-centred meringues and helpings of cream so generous they would have Tom Kerridge in sweats. This is proper nostalgic British cooking - and we bloody love it.

tip.text:
Troy Bar is pretty much the last bastion of soul in Shoreditch. This is a community-led, good-vibes bar that opens late and deals in tasty Caribbean food, cheap pints and live music; all from a lovably scruffy space that seems unchanged since the 90s. Forget upscale decor, drink deals or a PR presence – this is a simple, genuine operation focused on good people having a good time, with all the heart we can handle.

To enjoy it best, come for the live stuff. There's Tuesday's Spirit and Soul open mic night (past guests including Erykah Badu and Macy Gray); Reggae Thursdays; and Jazz Jam Fridays when super talented London musicians get together and create fire while captivated locals chomp on tasty jerk chicken (£7 plates), before the chairs get pushed to the side and a rare revelry unfurls. They simply don’t make ‘em like this anymore.

tip.text:
The biggest compliment you can hit a cocktail joint with is that it’s where the bartenders drink. That’s the deal with Happiness Forgets: a moody cocktail den lying in wait down the right steps in the right restaurant in Hoxton Square. Sure it ticks the conventional boxes: candle lit, bare bricked and seating only, but this has more about it than an amorous aura; this is about putting the art of cocktail making on a pedestal.

Here some of the friendliest, most knowledgeable staff around concoct unique potions that veer off the usual path, tailor made to suit the tastes of the most particular. Rather than ordering from the drinks list, tell them your story - yeah the whole thing - and see what they give you. But don’t forget to book, because happiness is all the rage right now.

text.text: Head into the restaurant at 8-9 Hoxton Square and make for the stairs, because some kind of joy is awaiting you. This is the kind of place where bartenders drink: moody lighting, cosy, great cocktails and some of the friendliest staff we've encountered on our numerous voyages. They're real eager to hit your spot so rather than ordering from the drinks list, tell them your story — yeah the whole thing — and see what they give you.
Best for... comfort food from the South Korean streets

tip.text:
We've long seen the queues outside OnTheBab, on Old Street, and wondered just what's going on inside. Well, it's food. South Korean comfort food to be a little more precise. A quick and casual place for dinner, come here to treat yourself and indulge. The spicy pork bun and the fried chicken with fried peanut were the dishes that really got us going. Let that rich sauce and flavour bring you happiness. That happiness won't last forever, but nothing really does.

Top Tip: keep an eye on the small window where you can either see the hands of a chef preparing the food or an actor pretending to be a chef preparing the food.

tip.text:
Leroy sits in a genre of restaurant that London certainly isn't short of. The wine is of the natural variety, the bread artisanal and the produce local, seasonal and of the highest quality. But there's something - a little indescribable something - that it does differently. Sure it has a Michelin star, but also it just gets us.

Is it the decor perhaps, which treads the line between smart and stylish so neatly? Or the extensive vinyl collection, neatly slotted above an open kitchen that kicks out palpable sex appeal? Whatever it is, it's a hella convivial place, serving quality European wine, classy bar snacks and some of the tastiest small plates in town. Expect the veggies to be bang on season; offal or seafood to be handled with care; and sauces to ooze the kind of savoury delights that require much sourdough mopping.

tip.text:
For such a lively area, plenty of the pubs in Shoreditch are much of a muchness, and you could well find yourself squished into an impossibly noisy sweatbox. The Owl and the Pussycat is probably our pick though, a listed building that dates back to the 17th century with Chesterfield sofas, mix and match furniture and stripped back walls.

Gets pretty busy but if you can work your way into one of their nooks and crannies, it's a dependable joint. Oh, and it also does food. It's one of those new 'gastropubs' if you can believe it.

Gets pretty busy but if you can work your way into one of their nooks and crannies, it's a dependable joint.
Best for... a cafe with a heart

tip.text:
We love a cafe with roots in the community, so Brick Lane's Kahaila is most certainly our bag. This not-for-profit operation serves ethically-sourced coffee, tasty homemade sandwiches and the kind of rich cakes we'd normally feel guilty chomping on.

Every month, their walls are filled with new works from local artists with every penny made from the artwork being ploughed back into the local community, plus if that wasn't enough they fund a women's shelter in the area. With a chilled-out vibe, excellent coffee and a conscience, what's not to dig about this place?

Best for... getting some culture

tip.text:
It's hard not to get a lil' lump in the throat thinking about Rich Mix. At a time when British society seems pretty divided, this is an altruistic melting pot of arts and creativity; a charity and social enterprise that houses the creative talents of people from all countries and cultures.

In a former leather factory spanning five floors, it puts on basically everything you can imagine: spoken word, gigs, theatre, dance, art shows and film screenings in its three screen cinema. You'll never really know what is going on there from week to week and that's the charm of it. Cultural diversity is what this huge institution is all about and we're all for it.

tip.text:
Compared to its big boy neighbours, Burmese food is underrated and underrepresented in LDN, but Lahpet are doing all they can to plant a big ol’ flag on the culinary map. From humble beginnings as a street food stall and then a Hackney warehouse, their popularity has resulted in a rather swish and swanky Shoreditch restaurant that's full of light woods, copper surfaces, and exposed bulbs.

But the food is the reason to come: distinctly fragrant Burmese concoctions like their iconic tea leaf salad, hearty noodle bowls, and rich meat and fish dishes. This is cooking from chefs unafraid to be bold - where you check the menu again after the first bite to work out what combo is causing that pleasure. The kind of eating experience where a smug, dazed grin will appear on your face after each bite.

text.text: Burmese food might be underrated and underrepresented, but Lahpet are doing all they can to plant a big old flag on London's culinary map. It certainly draws the foodie crowd in, ready to sample tasty, beautifully spiced Burmese concoctions. As has been their way throughout, it's about classic Burmese dishes given a twist of contemporary innovation: some small plates, salads (including their iconic tea leaf variation), bigger plates and hearty noodle bowls.
Best for... seductive drinks after dark

tip.text:
From the people who brought you Dalston's Three Sheets, favourite of many a cocktail connoseiur, comes the follow up: an amorous, dark and glossy den that's just ripe for romance. The operation is refreshingly simple: a short bar where bartenders shake, rattle and roll out the drinks to couples and groups hidden amongst the numerous dark, intimate nooks.

The cocktails, at £9-11, are some of the nicest we've sampled in London. They're always experimenting and changing up the menu - which we'd recommend asking the bartender to talk you through - but our nuts were invigorated by a light, bubbly French 75 and a dangerously drinkable Whisky + Milk. It's a seductive little spot that's just screaming out DATE NIGHT. But in a classy, subtle way of course.

Best for... fish like you've never had it

tip.text:
On the site of a former strip club in Shoreditch sits Brat, a real no-nonsense restaurant. Grill-master Tomos Parry learnt a thing or two in the good land we call Spain, but now he's back in London, doing his thing with some serious charcoal pits, cast iron equipment and a wood burning oven. You'll be wanting fish (brought over from Cornwall), grilled in what look like mini cages, and brought out with the crispiest skin and most succulent fish flesh you've had in a while. Expect seasonal veggies to be charred and smokey, vibes to be mighty convivial and all of it to arrive with a nice fat Michelin star.

Wash all this sultry goodness down with a refreshing glass of Amontillado sherry and tonic with grilled bay leaf garnish. Move aside G&Ts, there's a new drink in town.

tip.text:
Xi'an Impression has quietly been pumping out regional, authentic street food from north-western China to happy Highbury punters for years now. But not content to stay as a pokey hidden gem, they've made a leap for the big leagues with a comparatively vast canteen space on Commercial Street.

Despite feeling a little jaded that the suits and boots of Aldgate are now in on our secret, we're happy to report that the food is just as excellent, exciting and occasionally weird as it's always been. As with the original, the menu has a distinctly bitter and savoury theme, with oddities like black fungus and domes of boneless chicken that come swimming in rich, nutty sauces and oils, with hints of the Silk Road's Middle Eastern influences shining through. Our favourite new addition is the hand-pulled biangbiang noodles with cumin and lamb - the noodles thick and chewy and the lamb tender and richly seasoned in flavours that contrast beautifully with the East Asian textures.

text.text:
Having long pleased the punters of Highbury, Xi'an Impression have now spread their joy to a big canteen on Commercial Street. Here they're serving up some of their characteristically excellent, exciting, slightly weird noodle dishes full of eye-watering flavours.

As with the original, the menu has a distinctly bitter and savoury theme, with oddities like black fungus and domes of boneless chicken that come swimming in rich, nutty sauces and oils, with hints of the Silk Road's Middle Eastern influences shining through. And, with big hefty portions around the £10 mark, your bank account is gonna like this place almost as much as your tastebuds.
